Definition: In this task, we have popular claims that are fact checked by by PolitiFact, FactChecker.org and Washington Post. Classify the reviews of the claims that were raised and fact checked into one of the six categories: i) True, ii) Mostly True, iii) Half True, iv) False, v) Mostly False, and vi) Pants on Fire.

Positive Examples.input: Quotes Michelle Obama as saying, "White folks are what’s wrong with America."
Positive Examples.explanation: The output is the claim review that was made after fact checking and it was found that the claim was a completely false statement and Michelle Obama never said the statement.

Positive Examples.input: Says Facebook shut down a "Chick-Fil-A Appreciation Day."
Positive Examples.explanation: The given statement is half true as there was an event page posted by Facebook on Appreciation Day but since it did not violate any of Facebook's Guidelines and Policies, it was put back online.

Negative Examples.input: "BREAKING: 2 Democrat Congressmen On ISIS Payroll Arrested For Treason."
Negative Examples.explanation: Although the output is giving the same message as the correct review rating, it is not part of the given options to classify a claim into.

Negative Examples.input: Tom Suozzi raised taxes "by hundreds of millions of dollars" as Nassau County executive.
Negative Examples.explanation: The given claim needs to be classified into given six categories and it cannot have a numerical class.
